  "title": "高效学习的六个策略",
  "source": {
    "type": "article",
    "title": "高效学习的六个策略",
    "author": "Megan Sumeracki",
    "account": "The Learning Scientists",
    "accountOrDomain": "The Learning Scientists",
    "url": "https://www.learningscientists.org/blog/2016/8/18-1",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "id": "cn-guide-001",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "这篇文章把认知科学中比较可靠的学习方法整理成六个策略，包括间隔练习、提取练习、交错练习、精细化解释、具体例子和双重编码。它的价值在于提醒学习者：有效学习通常不是反复看材料，而是主动调动记忆、建立联系、分散练习并用不同方式表征知识。阅读时可以把六个策略看成互相配合的工具箱。例如，先用具体例子理解抽象概念，再用提取练习检查自己是否真的记住，之后通过间隔复习减少遗忘。对拾贝这样的复习产品来说，这篇文章也解释了为什么“做题、回忆、再反馈”会比单纯阅读更能促进掌握。"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-006",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Researchers have learned a great deal about how students learn on their own and in the classroom, and much of this research can be applied to educational settings. One of our primary goals is to make this research on learning more accessible and create free evidence-based resources for teachers and students. To meet that goal, over the past few months we have been working on creating resources in different formats based on 6 learning strategies whose effectiveness is backed by decades of cognitive research:"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-007",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Spacing (1)"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-008",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Retrieval Practice (2)"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-009",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Elaboration (3)"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-010",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Interleaving (4)"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-011",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Concrete Examples (5)"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-012",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Dual Coding (6)"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-013",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "All 6 of these strategies have evidence supporting their effectiveness, but some do have more evidence than others. For example, there is a lot of evidence supporting retrieval practice and spacing, whereas elaboration has more limitations. These certainly aren't the only effective learning strategies, either! We focused on these 6 because a recent report (7) found that few teacher-training textbooks cover these principles. Students are therefore missing out on mastering techniques they could use on their own to learn effectively. With our resources, we're trying to bring information about these particular learning strategies to teachers and students in easy-to-use formats."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-014",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "So far, we've designed single-page instructional posters that cover all the strategies - one poster per strategy . These posters were illustrated by former educator Oliver Caviglioli . We released the posters just last week, and since then have already seen thousands of downloads. We've been amazed at the excitement generated by these posters - multiple teachers have even shared pictures of their freshly printed posters on social media!"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-016",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "This week, we've also released sticker versions of each strategy . These stickers name the strategy, describe it with a simple phrase, and illustrate it. Teachers have already been in touch with us about many potential uses for these stickers: reminders for students to use the strategies - and for parents to remind them; a note to students about what strategy is most appropriate for a particular set of materials; positive reinforcement when students do use the strategies. The way these stickers are used will, of course, differ depending on what age group of students you are teaching. If you come up with additional uses, please do let us know!"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-017",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Coming next week: For the next six weeks, every Friday we will release one set of Powerpoint slides demonstrating one of the six strategies. Teachers will be able to use the slides in their classrooms to teach students how to learn effectively!"
      }
    ],
    "rawInput": "https://www.learningscientists.org/blog/2016/8/18-1"
  },
